column168: FURX120552 was found to be leaking on an interchange inspection by Train crew of the CCT railroad on 8-31-11 and this was reported to BNSF railway who stopped the leak. BNSF is going to file a 5800 report on this leak.  On 9-1-11 car was again found leaking on BNSf interchange track and leak from one of the bolts holding the cleanout and bottom outlet valve plate was leaking and a gain BNSF and CCT tightend the bolt stopping the leak. on 9/1/11 FRA then issued a one time verbal emergency move of 1.4 miles to the customer so that the car could be unloaded. FRA inspected the car with BNSF and CCT managers and then deemed car safe to move. Customer unloaed 9000 gallons of product on 9/1/11 and when car was checked again at 0600 on 9/2/11 car still not leaking at 0800 9/1/11 car was found leaking into containment vessel placed under the car in case car leaked and at 0845 CCT and customer personel again tightend the bolts on the bottom outlet valve plate and leak was stopped. The customer then completed the off load of the car at 1630 9/2/11. Car had just come from a shop on 1st trip after being relined.
column169: This car had just come out of a shop for relining and had the bottom outlet and the bottom outlet plate removed when the car was lined.  Car number FURX120552.  The shop alos removed the VRV, and the top fittings from the pressure plate on the car. After the car was relined there was no pressure test done on the car.    There is a posssibilty this car after being lined did not have a gasket placed on the bottom outlet plate or the new lining fouled the plate seat and this caused product to leak around the threads on the plate and leak out of the car. this material is corrosive and it could have stated to corrode the threads on the bolt and this allow the leak to start again once the bolt was tightened after the 1st leak was noticed and then to leak again after being tightened again for a 2nd time.  Had a proper pressure test been done the possible avenue for a leak would have been discovered

column168: On 9/02/2011 at 19:25 hrs; a CSXT conductor switching cars at the TRANSFLO Terminal was splashed by product. GATX 138, a loaded tank car of sulfuric acid, leaked from the top of the tank car. The car was isolated and PVS Chemicals Inc., Ohio EPA and CHEMTREC # 2011-09-02-00294 were notified.  Pettit Environmental, a CSXT response contractor and TRANSFLO personnel were dispatched to the scene and found a deteriorated and misaligned fill hole gasket.  The car was decontaminated and secured and the CSXT conductor washed off the affected area and returned to work.TRANSFLO will arrange with the shipper to have the fill hole gasket replaced prior to releasing the tank car back into transportation    This incident did require a special switching move.    Cause Code: 232 and 234    5 (5 + 5 ) (2 + 2) = 200    A QA 7.1 Non Conformance Report is not required for this incident.

column162: SENIOR MANAGER HAZARDOUS MATERIALS AND COMPLIANCE
column168: Reported by KCS' Jarian Pettus, Jackson yard, that switch crews while working in the east end of track number 4 detected Chlorine odor from one of two cars. The suspect cars are PPGX 1329 and PPGX 1382. Both tank cars are Residue Last Contained: Chlorine UN1017.  Two chlorep approved contractor responders from USES, Jackson, Mississippi were mobilized to the yard. Don Warren, with USES, responded and found leak originating from tank car PPGX 1329. Upon arrival the protective housing was found in the closed, pinned and sealed position. The protective housing seal was removed to access the fittings. The leak sourced from a loose B-end liquid valve (1/4 turn open) and a loose B-end secondary closure plug (hand tight). The B-end liquid valve was closed tight and the secondory closure plug was tightened tool tight correcting and stopping the release. The responder also found the other liguid valve and both vapor vavles loose (1/4 turn open) and all three secondary closure plugs were loose (one full turn to be tool tight). These were also closed and tightened by the responder.     Responders from EI DUpont, Delisle, MS responded to KCS Jackson, MS yard approximately three hours later to inspect the field mitigation efforts. The field work conducted by USES was approved. The protective housing was then closed, pinned and sealed. The PPGX was released back into transporation.       Shipper offered this tank car into transportation with the tank closures not completely tight. KCS emergency services were activated to provide for railroad safety qualified services to mitigate this emergency (e.g., special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, track protection and lockout, emergency response, management oversight, train/yard crew delay).  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 will apply for these services.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions.  The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While loading, one (1) 330-gallon tote was punctured by a forklift.  Approximately 70 gallons of resin solution were released inside the trailer.  Free product was immediately contained to trailer, and did not impact ground surface or environment.  Cyn Environmental Services of Dover, New Hampshire was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  Cyn Environmental Services used oil dry to contain/absorb the free product inside the trailer, and pumped the remaining product from the damaged tote.  Cyn Environmental Services proceeded to offload the trailer and wipe contaminated freight.  All free product was recovered, and trailer was reloaded, without further incident.  Five (5) 55-gallon drums of virgin product, and three (3) 55-gallon drums of spent oil dry were generated during cleanup activities.  Disposal was coordinated by Cyn Environmental Services in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  There were no injuries or exposures as a result of the release.

column168: On September 6, 2011 at 1627 hrs personnel in the CSXT Cumberland Yard discovered TILX 135314, a loaded tank car of Molten Sulfur with vapor leaking from the top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Imperial Oil, local, state and/or federal agencies were notified. CHEMTREC Report 2011090600216. CSX Hazardous Materials Manager and SPSI, a CSXT response contractor, discovered that the 1" air induction line did not have a cap applied. The cap was placed on the air induction line and the leak was secured and the car released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switching move. column168: Veolia employee was performing container piece count and container inspection while transloading containers from one van trailer to a different van trailer at the Veolia 10 day intransit facility located in Baytown, TX.  A pallet of drums containing hazardous materials was being transported up a ramp to the loading dock using a forklift. column168: Tank car GATX 62596 standing on a repair track in the railyard was reported by BNSF mechanical personnel that it was emanating a product odor from the top fill hole area. A detailed inspection of GATX 62596 revealed that 3 of the 4 fill hole securement bolts were not tool tight. Two of these securement bolts tended to slide away from the fill hole cover bolt slots when tool tightened. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder carefully tool tightened all loose securement bolts and wired them together in a cross pattern to ensure that the bolts would maintain their position against the fill hole cover. Afterwards, the product odor dissipated, as the fill hole cover was now providing a good closure seal.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: Tank car GATX 22314 in the railyard was reported with dried product residue on its side shell. A BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responder inspected GATX 22314 finding the manway closure as the leak source. Intact seal numbered 173493 was removed from the manway cover to ascertain the manway gasket condition; since a portion of the gasket was observed hanging over the manway nozzle lip. A 12 inch section of the manway gasket was found pinched and out of position which prevented a good closure seal. A shipper representative replaced the manway gasket with one supplied by BNSF during the morning of 9/06/2011. The manway cover was then secured after all manway securement bolts were properly tool tightened. Seals BNSF 06157795 and BNSF 06157760 were applied. Afterwards, the dried spillage on the shell of GATX 22314 was power washed and all captured cleaning solutions were solidified with clay absorbent and placed into a large disposal drum for appropriate disposal by the cleaning contractor. No soils were impacted by spillage or cleaning.
column169: Ensure shipper's pre-trip inspection process is fully implemented and validated as it relates to the total securement and mechanical fitness of all valves and fittings.

column168: DHL contacted ERTS to manage a UN1263 Paint release at the DHL facility located at 1801 Northwest 82nd Avenue in Miami, FL. ERTS dispatched Raider Environmental to manage the release. Raider Environmental personnel arrived on site to investigate the release and begin clean up operations. Raider Environmental personnel utilized absorbents to collect the .5 gallons of released product from the impacted trailer floor and also containerized the impacted boxes containing the cans of material. There were 106 boxes containing 6 one quart cans of material in each box. The contractor containerized 294 one quart cans, which were damaged along with the absorbents utilized to clean up the released material. All of the collected waste was containerized and transported for disposal. Three 55-gallon drums of waste were generated from clean up activities. There were 342 cans of material that were undamaged.

column168: A loaded rolloff box was parked at the intermediate truck transfer facility. A temporary repair was made and a shovelful of gravel from the ground along with the spilled material was placed back into the container.  The container continued without further incident to the intended waste disposal facility, where, when empty, the seal was replaced.

The car was isolated and the shipper Rock-Tenn, the state of GA DNR, the NRC and Chemtrec were notified (CHEMTREC Report # 2011-09-09-00134). The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative. SWS Environmental personnel contained the leak, transferred the product into TILX 260707 and washed the interior of the rail car.     This incident did require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is required for this incident.    Cause Code: 658  NARRI: 2 (5+3+0) X(2+0) = 32

column168: Per supervisor's report ~ driver hooked up & started unloading & didnt check the bleeder valve & walked away ~ resulted the EPA box to fill up & run over causing a spill of approx. 5 gallons of crude oil ~

1) A Boise, Idaho, Stores employee opened a 7 pound COMAT fiberboard box described on AWB 027 PDX 8711 1640 as "aircraft parts" with no outward indication of any hazardous material. Inside was another box. That inner package is shown in photo "PDX Tag.jpg" which had a component tag in a clear plastic sleeve, with a fluorescent pink label "ALWAYS SHIP HAZMAT." As can be seen in the photo, there is a trefoil symbol on the tag. This icon is used to flag hazardous materials in the parts system, TRAX. The part detail is attached as well, and shows that Horizon had already identified and communicated that the Emergency Locator Transmitter (ELT) is to be shipped as UN3091, Lithium metal batteries contained in equipment, 9, II.    2) The COMAT box traveled on flight 2593, operated by Q400 N423QX, which departed PDX at 19:54 and arrived BOI nonstop at 22:10 on September 6. The flight crew was not informed they were transporting hazmat, as there was no indication on the outer package, much less a shipping paper, available to cargo or ramp personnel that there was hazmat.    3) Horizon Air immediately began an investigation. Depending on the results of the investigation, an appropriate comprehensive fix and responsible party will be determined. All this will be in our 30-day written report.

column168: During a routine haz mat check, the driver discovered a small spill.  He put down spill pads to contain the leak and contained it to the floor of the trailer.  He then called his dispatcher and the New Jersey state police and reported the spill.   A Clean Harbors response crew arrived on scene, donned the appropriate personal protective equipment, entered the trailer and unloaded the leaking cubic yard box; the cubic yard box was repacked. The trailer floor was cleaned with a cleaning compound and returned to service for continued transport to intended disposal facility.
column169: At the time the container was accepted for transportation, no evidence of leaking or damage was observed. In order to prevent a recurrence, the personell who loaded the cubic yard box have been reminded to insure that a proper packaging and comprehensive inspection of a container's body along with the closure device to identify any potential issues before transportation.

THIS CAUSED A CRACK IN THE TOTE, CAUSING LESS THAN 5 GALLONS OF PRODUCT TO SPILL.  THE SPILL OCCURRED AND A LICENSED ER TEAM TRANSFERRED THE PRODUCT INTO ANOTHER TOTE UNTIL THE LIQUID WAS BELOW THE THE CRACKS IN THE TOTE.  THE NEW TOTE WAS FORWARDED ONTO DESTINATION PER SHIPPER'S AUTHORIZATION.  A LINED SALVAGE DRUM, PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED, WAS USED FOR THE CLEAN-UP AND AFFECTED MATERIALS. column169: DO NOT USE LIFT GATES TO CAPACITY.  LEAVE SEVERAL HUNDRED POUNDS OF LEEWAY FOR THE MAXIMUM CAPACITY.  TOTES, DRUMS, CYLINDERS AND PAILS OF CHEMICALS MUST BE COMPLETELY SHROUDED, BLOCKED AND BRACED USING MTY PALLETS, AIR BAGS, PLYWOOD AND/OR DUNNAGE.  WHEN HANDLING AND MOVING PAILS AND DRUMS, KNOW THE SURROUNDINGS TO ENSURE PRODUCT IS NOT EASILY DAMAGED.  TEMPORARY STORAGE AREAS FOR PACKAGES OF CHEMICALS AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS MUST BE KEPT IN A SAFE ENVIRONMENT TO PREVENT EASY DAMAGE.  RETRAINING IN WORK METHODS ON PROPER AND SAFE LOADING OF CHEMICALS.

column168: On September 7, 2011, a Covenant Transport tractor trailer carrying 11 totes of UN1790 Hydrofluoric Acid had an apparent load shift causing the front of the trailer to break open. The Conroe County Hazmat personnel initially responded and decon the area in 200 yards in each direction. ERTS dispatched Millstead Environmental to the site to investigate the incident and begin cleanup operations. After further investigation from the Conroe County Hazmat personnel it was determined that no release occurred due to this incident. The NRC was notified due to the roadway being closed for over two hours. Millstead Environmental personnel secured the totes on the trailer and then off loaded them onto the shoulder of the roadway utilizing a forklift. Millstead Environmental personnel then utilized the forklift to load the undamaged totes onto the replacement trailer provided by Covenant Transport. The totes of hydrofluoric acid were secured onto the trailer for continued transportation.     No release occurred due to this incident. The DOT 5800.1 Form was required and submitted due to the excessive road closure.

column168: Hazardous material shipment inspections jointly by California P.U.C. Transportation/Hazardous Material and U.S. Coast Guard inspectors in the intermodal hub revealed intermodal container TTNU 424891 that arrived previously on a BNSF train had a leaking drum within its lading that also had insufficient blocking and bracing. A 55 gallon poly drum was reported with free product on the top drum head near the bunghole closure cap-seal. TTNU 424891 was taken to the hub's containment area. No liquid product escaped from the intermodal container's interior. The beneficial shipper was notified and contract responders were dispatched. The responders reported that a loose bunghole cap-seal was found atop one of three like drums in the shipment. The loose bunghole cap-seal allowed some product to escape from the bunghole orifice during movement. The responders replaced the loose cap-seal with another suitable bunghole cap-seal, thus securing the bunghole. Spillage that mainly stayed atop the drum head was neutralized and then wiped. Response was concluded by 1600 hrs. PDT, 9/21/2011.
column169: No additional comments.

column168: Tank car UTLX 203403 was reported leaking product from the top valve housing area during movement in the railyard. Movement was stopped and no additional spillage noted on UTLX 203403's side shell. BNSF mechanical/hazardous material responders immediately inspected UTLX 203403. The responders reported finding the liquid valve not in the fully closed position and its closure plug only hand tight. The responders moved the liquid valve handle approximately 1/4 inch to fully close the valve. The liquid valve's closure plug was tool tightened. Securement was completed by 1450 hrs. CDT, 9/25/2011. Intact valve housing cover seal numbered 921651 was replaced by seal BNSF 313089. Spillage on the side shell evaporated and no ground impact from spillage was observed.

column168: NARRATIVE:   On 9/1/11 at 0855 a Code Yellow was called when the loader discovered Special Lactolite spilling out of the trailer's rear valve. Loader was in the process of a top load transload from R/C UTLX 500001 to Trimac trailer 47-1457. Loader noticed that the rear unloading valve was open and the cap was off that caused the release of approximately 50 gallons of product onto the ground. No drains were impacted. Carolina Emergency Response Team (CERT) was notified and is on site to assist in the clean up.  Code White was called at 1015.    AWARENESS ITEM:   1. This was the second Special Lactolite load of the day.  2. Rear unloading valve was open and cap was left off after tank completed washout.  3. Loader was trained on SSP and EDC on 8/22/11.  4. Ensure truck arrival inspections are thoroughly performed upon trailer arrival.     ROOT CAUSES:   1. Failure of loader and verifier to properly perform Haz-Mat Trailer Inspection due to their collective work load being heavy and their minds being off the task. By completing the inspection form properly, the point of failure (open valve and cap off) would have been identified and corrected.
column169: CORRECTIVE ACTION:   1. All loaders and verifiers have been instructed to follow the trailer inspection form with increased attention to detail and correct any issues prior to commencing the load.    2. Terminal management will work with personnel to ensure loads are split evenly, and focus their energies on engaging and assisting the Loaders in the yard.

column168: WHEN PULLING INTO MINUTE STOP PARKING LOT, THE TRAILER HIT THE POLE THAT IS IN FRONT OF THE PUMP, IT BROKE THE VALVES AND PRODUCT PIPING ON THE TRAILER.  FUEL LEAKED FROM THE UNDER PIPING ONLY.  THERE WAS A DEPUTY SHERIFF AT THE LOCATION AT THE TIME.  THE DRIVER, TERRY BRISTOW, ASKED HIM TO CALL "911" AND THEN GOT THE SPILL KIT OUT OF THE TRUCK AND BEGAN TO USE THE SPILL RAGS TO STOP THE SPREAD OF THE FUEL, IT NEVER SPREAD BEYOND THE PAVEMENT.  DIXIE VOLUNTEER FIRE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND CONFIRMED THAT THE FUEL HAD NOT SPREAD PAST THE PAVEMENT, THEY SPREAD OUT SOME OF THE OIL DRY ABSORBANT.  OUR MAINTENANCE DEPARTMENT ARRIVED AND CLEANED UP EVERYTHING.  THE TRUCK WAS MOVED AND UNLOADED THEN TAKEN TO THE AUTO SHOP, TRANSPORT SERVICES, FOR REPAIRS. THEY ESTIMATED THAT AMOUNT OF FUEL SPLIT WOULD HAVE BEEN ABOUT 20 GALLONS IF THE LINES HAD OF BEEN COMPLETELY FULL.

column168: A Veolia employee picked up a drum containing a mixture of Waste/Used Sodium Hydroxide Solution which was filled by the shipper. All leaked liquid was absorbed, removed and repackaged.

column168: On 09/19/2011 at 0926 hours, personnel in the CSX Intermodal Tampa Terminal discovered UMXU 246030 a loaded intermodal freight container of Corrosive Liquids NOS (acetic acid, anhydride), 8, UN 2920, PG II leaking from the rear doors. The freight container was isolated and UPS and Chemtrec were notified, report #20110919 00188.  CSXI emergency response contractor EMI dispatched SWS to the scene and found one 275 gallon plastic tote with metal cage surrounding leaking. Heavy top loaded freight fell over and crushed the tote causing the leak.. The issue identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, UPS Andy Stroud 502-359-2991. Contractor personnel cleaned up the spilled material and leak was secured. The remaining lading was transloaded into two freight containers for proper loading (non-double stack) and blocking/bracing.      This incident did not require a special switching move.  The 7.1 is not required.     Cause Code: 660  NARRI: 5 (5+5+0) x (4+0) = 200
column169: Notified shipper to refer to the Inteermodal Loading Guide for proper loading and blocking/bracing methods; preventing top heavy frieght.

column168: On 9/3/11, Bobtail transport vehicle B-57 was transporting a load of diesel fuel to Carville Job Corps Center.  We had extremely stormy weather conditions due to Tropical Storm Lee.  At 09:23 on Point Clair Road approx. 1/2 mile from the delivery point, the driver lost control and the truck rolled onto its side and into the roadside ditch.  The driver was not injured except for a bruised arm, and was able to climb out of the truck on his own.  There were no other injuries and no other people or vehicles were involved in the accident.  There was no personal property damage other than the area of the spill.  A passer-by called 911,and the driver called our Dispatcher, John Disotelll and notified him of the rollover and that diesel was leaking from the cargo tank.  John immediately started calling the State Police Hotline number, which was busy, and departed for the accident site.  The St. Gabriel Fire Dept. arrived at 09:31, and noted that one of the 700-gallon compartments was leaking from the void space, and approx. 12 - 15 gallons of diesel was on the ground at that point.  The fire dept. called DOTD and requested two loads of sand, one for the spill and another for the ditch to prevent runoff.  John dispatched a second driver and bobtail to off-load the diesel, and he and the second driver loaded absorbent pads and boom from the warehouse.  State Police Trooper Lewis arrived at approx. 11:00.  John and the Robert Distr. bobtail and driver arrived at 11:14 to begin offloading diesel.  John finally got through to the Louisiana Hazmat Hotline, and he and the driver began containing the discharged diesel.  City of St. Gabriel backhoe was on scene.  The fire chief requested DOTD dispatch a dump truck with spreader.  Iberville Parish dump truck arrived with sand at 11:23.  United States Environmental Services Group (USES) was called around 11:30 to continue cleanup.  LDEQ arrived on scene at 12:26.  DOTD arrived with spreader at 12:35.  USES arrived at 12:45, met with Hazmat Trooper Lewis and assessed the incident.  USES proceeded to drill the tank truck to remove and transfer the product to the Robert bobtail.  Transfer was completed by 14:45.  Once the damaged truck was recovered, cleanup was resumed at approximately 16:30.  Water provided by the fire dept. was used to wash the diesel to one end and recover it with a vacuum truck.  LDEQ was on site to oversee the cleanup.  USES worked until 21:00, at which time they left due to severe weather conditions.  USES returned on 9/4/11 to continue the cleanup with the assistance of the local fire dept.  Cleanup was completed by 11:30, and sorbent boom was left in place at recommendation of LDEQ.  Recovered product was sent for disposal to A3M in Reserve, LA.  On 9/9/11, USES returned on site with LDEQ for recommendations of further remediation.  LDEQ suggested bio-remediation with Micro Blaze and fertilizer and leave sorbent boom in place until first rainfall.  On 9/12/11, USES returned on site to apply t

column168: Quality Carriers - Claim Number: 31598    On September 16, 2011, a Quality Carriers tanker was off loading UN3264 Ferric Sulfate when the hose came off the valve and sprayed approximately 15 gallons of material onto the bay door and wall of the facility and also impacted an area of the concrete parking lot measuring approximately 25' by 25'. ERTS dispatched an environmental contractor (Atlantic Response) to cleanup the release. Atlantic response personnel neutralized the material, applied absorbents and then collected all of the waste for disposal. Six drums of waste were generated from cleanup activites and were left onsite until the waste has been approved by the disposal factility to be transported and disposed of. No storm drains, waterways or soils were impacted as a result of this release.

column168: While unloading this trailer, DSR noticed a clear liquid on the side and floor beneath a tote bin he was removing, the bin had proper wood dunnage around it. Upon closer inspection, he found a one inch cut on one of the top corners of the plastic tote bin. As the bin was transported to LFY, liquid splashed around inside the bin and came out of the cut on the top corner. Once discovered, I placed the IBC bin in the hazardous materials bay, called the Regional Safety Manager, Chemtrec, the Louisiana State Police, and the shipper to report. The shipper sent out a recovery team to transfer the product into 2 new IBC bins,and recovered all contaminated items, which included the damaged IBC bin, a skid of fiberglass grating, wood dunnage, and approximately a 5ft by 8 ft section of the trailer floor which the product had leaked onto. The two new bins were placed back in the haz. mat. bay and will be sent back to the shipper as soon as they send proper shipping papers for transportation.

According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While offloading,a mechanical failure occurred to the fitting valve, which resulted in the release of approximately 2 gallons of free product.  Product sprayed onto the clothing and face shield worn by Slay Transportation Co., Inc. employee, and the concrete ground surface beneath loading tank.  The customer, AUT Brenham, applied sand and sorbent material to the free product, which was recovered and containerized, in accordance with regulations.  The Slay Transportation Co., Inc. driver  replaced contaminated mask and clothing, washed his skin with soap and water, and did not experience symptoms of exposure or any reaction to sprayed product.  Mechanic responded to assist in faulty connection, and offload proceeded without further incident.  No further action was required.
column169: Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: According to the information obtained, the following occurred.  While offloading at customer location, Michelin, a leak occurred from the hose.  Apparently, the hose and coupling separated during offload, which resulted in the release of approximately 100 gallons of free product.  The free product sprayed onto the Slay Transportation Co., Inc. and Michelin operators, and released to the asphalt surface within the parking lot.  Slay Transportation Co., Inc. and Michelin operators thoroughly washed sprayed areas and clothing, and continued without further incident.  There were no symptoms of exposure or reactions reported.  Michelin environmentalists applied absorbent pads to contain the free product, and A&D Environmental of Greenville, South Carolina was dispatched to perform the cleanup.  The free product was contained to an impervious surface, and did not migrate to surface soils or waters of the state.  A&D Environmental recovered spent absorbents and free product, which were containerized, pending disposal in accordance with local, state, and federal regulations.  No further action was required.
column169: Slay Transportation Co., Inc. will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures to all personnel.

column168: Driver was traveling SB on SR 821 when he attempted to exit ramp 31.  Driver attempted to exit highway on to ramp at too high of speed causing a one vehicle overturn accident.  At this time it is not known the exact location of package failure, however the cargo tank did separate from the chassis.  Duration of release was believed to be over several hours as the emergency responders were figuring out how to recover tank out of swale.  It was finally determined to use a vacuum truck to transfer remaining fuel out of separated cargo tank into another company truck.  Recovered product was 1,100 gallons.  Emergency Environmental Response Company diked off all drains leading into swale (final resting location of cargo tank).  Drains only drained one way into swale, and did not lead into any other water systems.  Only impact was to surface soil.  Remediation cleanup is completed at this time.  Sampling shows there was no impact to ground water and soil samples are all within Florida state guidelines after cleanup.
column169: We are going to stress to our drivers that posted speed limits on exit ramps are for cars, and not commercial vehicles.  When applicable, approach exit ramp 10 mph  slower than post exit speed limit.  Drivers need to be in a position to accelerate through exit ramp, not decelerate.

column168: PACKAGE WAS DISCOVERED INSIDE UPS TRUCK DURING UNLOAD.  THE PACKAGE WAS LEAKING FROM INSIDE OUT, LEAVING A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID ON TOP SHELF OF TRUCK.  I RESPONDED TO THE PACKAGE INSIDE THE TRUCK, TESTED THE LIQUID WITH PH ON SHELF; CAME BACK 0-1.  I THEN NEUTRALIZED THE LIQUID AND SOLIDIFIED.  I CONTINUED TO MOVE THE PACKAGE TO DMP AREA FOR FURTHER CLEANUP.  UPON OPENING THE BOX, I DISCOVERED THE INNER BOX WAS SURROUNDED BY PACKING PEANUTS AND WAS LEAKING THROUGH ONTO OUTER BOX.  BOTH BOXES SHOWED NO SIGNS OF PUNCTURE, DENTS, RIPS, TEARS OR TAMPERS.  BOTH BOXES DID NOT HAVE ANY HAZARD LABEL MARKING, NO SHIPPING PAPERS AND NO OTHER MARKINGS TO INDICATE REGULATED MATERIAL.   AFTER OPENING THE INNER PACKAGE I FOUND THAT CONTAINER WAS CRACKED NEAR THE TOP OF THE BOTTLE AND LEAKED OUT, CONTAMINATING 3 OTHER BOTTLES.  ALL CONTAMINATED BOTTLES WERE PROPERLY SOLIDIFIED.

column168: Railcar UTLX 802756 was loaded in the Geismar Facility containing 35% HCL and shpped.  Closure report showed no leakage.   When railcar arrived at Rail yard in Odessa TX the railcar was found leaking on a pinhole in the jacket on a weld seam on the side of the railcar.  The West Texas and Lubbock Railway pushed the railcar into the customer location.  It was assumed that 30 gallons of HCL was spilled on the rail tracks while pushing the railcar into Cooper Energy's yard.  The spill was decontaminated and the railcar was offloaded and emptied.  The railcar is owned by the customer and not Univar.  Univar dispatched three operators from Odessa yard to rail yard site. It was determined that a leak developed on the under side of the railcar in a weld seam.  The car was pushed into the customer location and emptied.  Estimated quantity based on volume is 30 gallons.
column169: No recommendations at this time.    Railcar had been in prior service.   Post fill and pre trip inspections were completed.   Appears non preventable.

column42: ETHANOL OR ETHYL ALCOHOL OR ETHANOL SOLUTIONS OR ETHYL ALCOHOL SOLUTIONS
column168: (A)A BNSF unit ethanol train derailed eight tank cars on the north wye at the junction to the Texas City Terminal Railway. The cause of this derailment is under investigation.SHPX 208400 derailed on its side with liquid product releasing from the undamaged vacuum relief valve (VRV). Responders placed a catch receptacle under the leaking VRV and slowed the release rate by propping close the valve stem of the VRV. Afterwards, the VRV product release was slowed to drips and then ceased when SHPX 208400 was up-righted. Air monitoring was established and continued until all derailed equipment were up-righted/rerailed. No adverse conditions were noted during the air monitoring process. The remaining product in SHPX 208400 was transferred into another suitable tank car without further incident on 9/22/2011. No ground impact was evident from any non-evaporated spillage. (B) A BNSF unit ethanol train derailed eight tank cars on the north wye at the junction to the Texas City Terminal Railway. The cause of this derailment is under investigation.  SHPX 206740 derailed on its side with intermittent product drips emanating from the undamaged vacuum relief valve (VRV) and from around the undamaged liquid valve body. Responders placed catch receptacles under the leaking VRV and liquid valve. Product drips ceased when SHPX 206740 was up-righted. Air monitoring was established and continued until all derailed equipment were up-righted/rerailed. No adverse conditions were noted during the air monitoring process. The remaining product in SHPX 206740 was transferred into another suitable tank car without further incident on 9/22/2011.  No ground impact was evident from any non-evaporated spillage.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING ON INTERSTATE 26 EASTBOUND NEAR MILE MARKER 54 THE TRACTOR WAS INVOLVED IN A ROLLOVER.  THE ISO-TANK WAS DETACHED FROM THE CHASSIS AND CAME TO A REST IN THE MIDDLE OF INTERSTATE 26.  THE SC DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH AND ENVIRONMENTAL CONTROL, SC HIGHWAY PATROL AND THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO ASSESS THE SITE.  THE INTERSTATE WAS SHUT DOWN UNTIL PROPER MEASURES COULD BE TAKEN TO RECOVER THE ISO-TANK.  HEPACO, INC. WAS DISPATCHED TO INSPECT THE ISO-TANK. HEPACO, INC. ARRIVED ON-SCENE AND INSPECTED THE ISO-TANK AND CONFIRMED THAT THERE AWAS NO LEAK FROM THE ISO-TANK. A CRANE WAS USED TO LOAD THE ISO-TANK ONTO A LOWBOY TRAILER AND SECURED. THE UNIT WAS RELOCATED TO THE PILOT TRUCK STOP PENDING FURTHER INSTRUCTIONS.  AFTER REPAIRS TO THE INTERSTATE WERE COMPLETED, THE INTERSTATE WAS RE-OPENED.  THE INTERSTATE WAS SHUT DOWN FOR APPROXIMATELY 12 HOURS.  ON SEPTEMBER 6, 2011 THE ISO-TANK WAS RELOADED ONTO A CHASSIS AND TRANSPORTED TO EASTMAN CHEMICAL IN KINGSPORT, TN.  AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT A SMALL AMOUNT OF VEHICLE FLUIDS WERE RELEASED AND IMPACTED SOME SOIL.  ON SEPTEMBER 6, 2011 HEPACO, INC. RETURNED TO THE SITE AND REMOVED THE CONTAINMENT SOIL FROM THE IMPACTED AREA. HEPACO, INC. WILL COORDINATE DISPOSAL OF THE WASTE GENERATED AS A RESULT OF THE INCIDENT.
column169: SINCE THE RELEASE WAS ACCIDENTAL, NO PLANS CURRENTLY EXIST TO PREVENT RECURRENCE. HOWEVER, P&S TRUCKING WILL CONTINUE TO REINFORCE SAFETY GUIDELINES AND HANDLING PROCEDURES TO ALL PERSONNEL.

column168: On 09/22/2011 at 2120 hours personnel in the CSXT Pascagoula, MS yard discovered rail cars CPDX 582160, CPDX 582123, CPDX 582003, CPDX 582069, all residue tank cars of Sulfur, Molten, emitting and odor from the manway area. The cars were isolated and the shipper, Tiger-SUL, the local fire department, the Mississippi Department of Environmental Quality and CHEMTREC, report 2011-0922-00294, were notified. United States Environmental Services (USES), a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found all of the manway bolts less than tool tight and all four cars were missing the manway gaskets. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper's representative,. USES personnel replaced the missing gaskets and properly secured the manway bolts. The leak was secured and the car released for transport.     This incident did not require a special switching move.  A QA 7.1 Non conformance report is not required for this incident.    Cause Code: 200  NARRI 5(4+1+0) X (2+0) = 50

column168: ON 09/20/2011 AT APPROXIMATELY 1900 HOURS, CHAD LANDRUM WAS DRIVING EASTBOUND ON TEXAS SH-152.  AS HE TOPPED A SMALL INCLINE IN THE HIGHWAY, HE OBSERVED A TRACTOR/TRAILER IN THE WESTBOUND LANE SLOWING TO A SPEED TO MAKE A LEFT TURN.  CHAD OBSERVED THAT THE ONCOMING TRACTOR/TRAILER BEGAN MAKING HIS LEFT TURN, ENTERING THE EASTBOUND LANE OF WHICH HE WAS TRAVELING.  CHAD THEN APPLIED HIS BRAKES AND STEERED HIS VEHICLE TO THE RIGHT TO AVOID IMPACT WITH THE TRACTOR/TRAILER CROSSING INTO HIS EASTBOUND LANE TO MAKE A LEFT TURN TO PROCEED SOUTHBOUND.  THE TRACTOR/TRAILER CONTINUED ITS LEFT TURN AND COLLIDED WITH CHAD, STRIKING HIS VEHICLE ON THE DRIVER'S SIDE.  THE IMPACT RIPPED A HOLE INTO CHAD'S TRAILER, SPILLING THE CONTENTS AND BEING IGNITED BY THE FRICTION OF THE TWO VEHICLES.  CHAD'S VEHICLE ROLLED OVER ONTO ITS TOP.  POLICE, FIRE AND AMBULANCE WERE DISPATCHED TO THE ACCIDENT.  SH-152 WAS CLOSED FOR APPROXIMATELY 2 HOURS BY EMERGENCY PERSONNEL.

column168: On September 29, 2011, a 30-gallon drum was crushed during transportation resulting in the release of approximately 2 ounces of material. The released product impacted the top of the drum. An environmental contractor was dispatched to the site and overpacked the damaged drum.

CTL Transportation contacted ERTS to manage a Sodium Hypochlorite Solution 10-15 (bleach) release at a Water Treatment Plant located at 525 West Houston Blvd. in Houston, TX. It was reported that the tractor (C14632) trailer (C24787) pressurized resulting in the dome lid coming loose and releasing approximately 5 gallons of bleach onto the concrete driveway and also impacted an area of soil along the driveway as well. ERTS dispatched Milstead Environmental to manage the release and perform cleanup activities. Milstead Environmental personnel neutralized the released material and then applied absorbents to the impacted concrete driveway, collected all of the impacted absorbents and containerized the waste for disposal. Milstead Environmental also hand excavated the minimal area of soil that was impacted along the concrete driveway, which was also containerized for transportation and disposal. Milstead Environmental personnel took soil samples, which came back clean and then back filled the area with fresh soil. No storm drains or waterways were impacted as a result of this release.

CN mechanical department employee noted a small amount of product dripping from the bottom outlet cap on tank car UTLX 200048(L / N-Propyl Acetate) during an inspection at the CN Glen Yard, Chicago, IL. All appropriate departments notified, tank car isolated. CN's response team responded noting the bottom outlet valve handle in the closed position, shipper's seal intact and product dripping from the cap area. Further inspection noted the cap was tool tight. An attempt was made to re-secure the cap, which reduced the frequency of the dripping, but did not stop it. Patching material was applied to the cap threads, which stopped the leak. The consignee and FRA Hazardous Materials Inspector M. Bennett were notified of the repairs and the consignee agreed to accept the tank car for off-loading. Inspector Bennett issued a verbal authorization to move the car a short distance to the consignee's facility to facilitate the safe off-loading of product. Tank car released and moved to destination without incident. Shipper to obtain a written DOT OTMA to a repair facility.

During remote control switching operations in the railyard, railcars switched from the lead into a yard track with standing railcars impacted and derailed an empty covered hopper resulting in this hopper's closed coupler knuckle to puncture the A-end tank head of PPRX 28538 that was motionless in front of the covered hopper. Incident cause attributable to passed couplers. Escaping product vapors from PPRX 28538 ignited and the ensuing fire consumed the preponderance of the lading within PPRX 28538.  The primary fire at PPRX 28538 was extinguished by 1330 hrs. CDT, 9/16/2011. Collateral fires surrounding PPRX 28538 were fully extinguished by 1630 hrs. CDT, 9/16/2011. Several rail cars in the railyard surrounding PPRX 28538 incurred significant fire and heat related damages along with the laid rail in the yard tracks. Impacted soils containing some free product, fire-fighting foam and water were excavated and stockpiled within the railyard upon plastic sheeting for future analysis and appropriate disposal. Additional soil sampling around the incident site is scheduled.

column168: Employee was unloading the trailer when the noticed the spill.  He called his supervisor to the location of the spill and stated that he was not responsible for the damage.  His supervisor inspected the blades on his forklift and they did not appear to have any paint residue.  His supervisor inspected the drum and observed a pin-hole puncture of the bottom of the drum.  His supervisor then  inspected the area of the trailer and saw a protuding nail where the drum was placed.  We removed the drum from the trailer and loaded it into a larger salvage drum.  The shipper had loaded the drums.

DRUM HAD BROKEN THROUGH THE SKID IT WAS ON AND ANOTHER PUT UNDERNEATH. WHILE TRYING TO MOVE THE UPPER SKID OVER ON THE LOWER ONE A FORK PUNCTURED THE DRUM AT THE POINT THAT HAD BROKEN THROUGH THE SKID. DRUM WAS IMMEDIATELY TIPPED ON ITS SIDE THE REDUCE THE AMOUT SPILLED AND FLOOR DRY PLACED AROUND THE SKID TO CONTAIN WHAT HAD ALREADY SPILLED.  ISOLATED AREA UNTIL THE ARRIVAL OF HAZMAT VENDOR.

column168: ACCORDING TO THE INFORMATION OBTAINED, THE FOLLOWING OCCURRED. WHILE TRAVELING, THE US WATER SERVICES' VEHICLE SWERVED TO AVOID A THIRD PARTY, WHICH CAUSED THE TRUCK TO ENTER INTO MEDIAN, AND IGNITE INTO FLAMES.  THE FIRE CAUSED EXTENSIVE DAMAGE TO THE TRACTOR AND TRAILER, WHICH WAS A TOTAL LOSS.  THEREFORE, RESPONDERS WERE NOT ABLE TO DETERMINE A RELEASE AMOUNT, AS THE MAJORITY OF DIESEL FUEL AND CARGO WERE BURNED ALONG WITH THE VEHICLE.  THE TRAILER CONTAINED VARIOUS QUANTITIES OF WATER TREATMENT CHEMICALS, WHICH CONSISTED OF THE FOLLOWING: BWT 360, SHIPPED AS UN1719, CAUSTIC ALKALI LIQUID, N.O.S., CLASS 8, PG II - ONE (1) 55-GALLON DRUM; CWT 530A, SHIPPED AS UN 3267, CORROSIVE LIQUID, BASIC, ORGANIC, N.O.S, CLASS 8, PG-III - TWO (2) 55-GALLON DRUMS; CWT 530, SHIPPED AS UN3267, CORROSIVE LIQUID, BASIC, ORGANIC, N.O.S., CLASS 8, PG III - ONE (1) 55-GALLON DRUM;  RO 503, NON-REGULATED - ONE (1) 275-GALLON TOTE; PHYTOUT V, NON-REGULATED - TWO (2) 55-GALLON DRUMS. THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE SITE ALONG WITH GIBBS TOWING OF WILLISTON, NORTH DAKOTA.  GIBBS TOWING ASSISTED IN REMOVING WRECKAGE FROM THE SITE, AND COORDINATED EXCAVATION AND DISPOSAL OF IMPACTED SOILS, IN ACCORDANCE WITH LOCAL, STATE, AND FEDERAL REGULATIONS.  THERE WERE NO INJURIES OR EXPOSURES REPORTED AS A RESULT OF THE RELEASE.
column169: US Water Services will continue to train and reinforce safe handling procedures and driver safety to all personnel.

column168: Hazardous Materials Incident Synopsis    Events of September 21, 2011    On September 21, 2011 Environmental Options, Inc. picked up three containers of lab packed chemicals from the former McKee Craft facility located at 404 Sandy St, Fairmont, NC, 28340. The  facility  is  presently  in  bankruptcy  and  Community  South  Lending  of  Tennessee  is overseeing the facility closure which includes removal of wastes abandoned by McKee Craft. Steve Gross of Community South contacted Global Environmental Assurance to provide waste removal services.  Jimmy Beliveau, Global Environmental Assurance, PO Box 337, St. George, SC 29477 packaged the material for shipment and contacted Environmental Options, Inc. to transport to the disposal facility.   At the point of pick-up Key Mckee signed the manifest certifying that the waste was "classified, packaged, marked and labeled/placarded and are in all aspects in proper condition for transport according to applicable international and national government regulations." As determined later, this was not the case. During the investigation of the  incident  it  was  determined  the  materials  were  improperly  packaged and  prepared  for shipment by Global Environmental Assurance (Jimmy Beliveau). Specifically the following has been determined:    1.  The MEKP containers contained holes and were placed in the containers with packing material.  2.  Improper  packing  materials-the  absorbent  seemed  to  be  a  residential  kitty  litter containing odor control crystals which would be incompatible with MEKP.   This incompatibility would cause an exothermic reaction if the two came in contact with one another which would be highly likely when containers with holes were placed in the drums.  3.  The items were placed on top of the packing material not surrounded by and cushioned to prevent breakage or leaking and to maintain the container in an upright position during transport.  4.  A creme hardener containing 30-60% benzoyl peroxide was packed with the MEKP and would be incompatible with the MEKP and should have been packaged separately.     It is our belief that the fire on our vehicle was a direct result of improper packaging by Global Environmental Assurance (Jimmy Beliveau). Key Mckee also certified by his signature that the material was properly packaged.    During transport the driver of the transport vehicle noticed smoke coming from the rear of his trailer and pulled to the side of the road.  A police officer from the Suffolk Police department pulled in behind him.  The Suffolk Fire department was notified and responded along with the Portsmouth and Chesapeake Hazmat teams.   The Hazmat team made entry into the trailer and determined that 2 drums of organic peroxides had been on fire but at this point the fire was out and the situation was stable.  A private company, PetroChem was contracted to complete the repacking of materials and to insure that all remaining containers were not compromised during the i

(SEE ATTACHMENT III)  WE WILL NO LONGER DO BUSINESS WITH GLOBAL ENVIRONNENTAL ASSURANCE, THE BROKER RESPONSIBLE FOR PACKING THE MATERIAL INVOLVED IN THE INCIDENT. (SEE ATTACHMENT IV)

column168: NARRATIVE:   On 9/26/11 at approximately 11:55 hrs an estimated 1 quart of Caustic Soda was released. A Transfer was being conducted between railcar (GATX 49425) and a single compartment trailer (22059) with a single dome. The loader noticed product leaking down the side of the railcar. The loader climbed to the top of the railcar and noticed product leaking from the jumper hose between the Air tee valve and the Product tee valve. The loader closed the product valve and then called code yellow. The product was contained inside the track pans; no product contacted the ground, water or drains.  Team members responded to the code yellow and immediately brimmed and dike inside the track pan. Vinegar used to neutralize, and sand was used absorb the Caustic.     AWARENESS ITEMS:   1. The Terminal Manager re-reviewed the SSP for transferring corrosive product via blower pac/air compressor on 8-9-2011  2. Ensure all valves, fittings, hoses and tools required to perform the assigned task are inspected as part of the daily inspection.    3. The ruptured airline was replaced 2 weeks ago.    4. The Loader was fully trained on this transfer and demonstrated proficiency.
column169: ROOT CAUSES:  1. Loader inadvertently opened the product valve and introduced product to the air line.    2. The jumper hose between air valve assembly and the product valve assembly ruptured when product was introduced.      CORRECTIVE ACTIONS:  1. Retrain all employees to ensure valves are operated in accordance to the SSP.  Re-training will be documented on Form 1686.    2. The air line was taken out of service and was replaced after the rupture.

column168: NARRATIVE:   On 9/30 at 9:05am, the Crew Leader noticed Sulfuric Acid on the side of railcar GATX 5855. Code yellow was announced and several team members responded.  A Loader, in all the required PPE, climbed to the top of the railcar and identified liquid seeping from the product hose.  He re-positioned the product and the leak stopped.     AWARENESS ITEM:   1. All product hose gaskets have recently been changed.   2. All sulfuric acid and caustic valves are inspected prior to being put into service.   3. Leak started 15 minutes after the transfer was completed.
column169: ROOT CAUSES:  1. Equipment failure: Product hose gasket leaked between product hose and product valve connection due to the alignment of the hose to the product valve.      CORRECTIVE ACTION:   1. Recommended to TRANSFLO that a 45 degree fitting be installed between the product hose and valve, to allow for direct alignment and reduce the weight on the connection.

column168: This loaded tank car, BIGX 1019, Argon Refrigerated Liquid, was discovered leaking in arriving train Q-SHKC-21 to the Kansas City, MO yard. Upon inspection there was liquid Argon spilling out of the cabinet doors. The doors were opened and the release point was a liquid line bleeder valve. The response crew closed the valve to stop the release.  The cabinet was left open for an hour to allow the frost to clear and the piping to further thaw. There were no additional leaks observed.    Also, there was a defect found with the hazmat shpping document provided by shipper via their EDI service provider RSI Logistics. Specifically, the proper shipping name was incorrect.    File Note: Item 27--Amount in package was estimated by this report preparer because the exact information is not available to carrier. Shipper provided bulk quantity on shipping paper as 1 Tank Car, per DOT requirements.    KCS emergency services were activated to provide for railroad safety qualified services to mitigate this emergency (e.g., special switching for safety isolation, yard service interruption, Critical Incident Desk notifications, emergency response, management oversight, train/yard crew delay, and regulatory notification reports).  KCS Switching Terminal Tariff 8100 Item 860 and KCS Rules Publication Tariff 9011 + 9012 Item 260 may apply.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway (KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases (NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adjacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases (a.k.a. package closure defects such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS. The Association of American Railroads (AAR) hazmat inspector (aka BOE inspector) will follow up to all Non Accident Releases (NAR) to assist hazmat shipper with regulatory requirements and training to help prevent recurrence of unsafe transportation conditions. column168: Star Transportation's driver arrived at the Clarksville distribution center and when to the main terminal office to get tank readings for his delivery. After being shown to deliver into tanks 1 & 2 , he proceeded to hook up to them inside the containment dike. He admittedly hooked up to the fittings 3 & 4 by mistake, the tanks overfilled and sprayed out of the vents on top of the tanks. The driver shut down the pumps as soon as he saw the fuel spray. United States Environment Services (USES) responded with a Vac-Truck and man power to clean and remove the diesel. Dirt was removed from a small area that sprayed over the containment wall, photos and soil test were taken at the site, tanks and site were power washed then treated with miroblaze.

column168: At around noon on 9/29, a loader at Wurtland was splashed with 95% sulfuric acid while finishing the final stages of the pressure check before releasing the tank car into transport. The operator was wearing hard hat, glasses and leather gloves.  It is unclear what happened next but his partner had just left him to go finish some paperwork when he heard him yell for help.   The load partner stepped out of the loaders office and saw the other loader running towards him with acid dripping from his face and torso area.  Several other employees nearby heard the loader yell for help and assisted with placing him in a safety shower.   The plant immediately launched into a full response mode and called for medical helicopter to transport the individual to a nearby burn hospital based on their assessment of his condition.  The as found condition of the rail car was: pressure test air hose disconnected, vent valve closed, and midland cap removed (no gasket in cap).      Step Failure Event Date Time  1 Cars on spot 29-Sep-11 7:00  2 Started loading car on #2 Spot 29-Sep-11 9:00  3 Finished loading car on #2 Spot 29-Sep-11 11:00  4 Operator B leaves for the safety meeting and delivers sample to control room 29-Sep-11 11:15  5 Operator B returns to rack and observes Operator A closing #2 spot car.  Indicated that normal PPE (hard hat, gloves, and glasses) were worn.  No pink suit coverage at this time.  Operator B heard the air going into the car 29-Sep-11 12:05  6 Operator B tells Operator A he is going to do paperwork.  Operator A gets water, and sits down in the chair inside the operator loader shack 29-Sep-11 12:15  7 Operator B hears a noise that sounded like a release 29-Sep-11 12:20  8 Operator B hears Operator A call for help but did not immediately recognize what the noise was.  Operator B stands up, looks outside the loading shack and sees acid spray from car. 29-Sep-11 12:20  9 Operator B radios for help  29-Sep-11 12:30  10 Operations personnel document as found condition 29-Sep-11 13:30    approximately 2140 lbs of the spilled material was contained in secondary containment and pumped to the site elementary neutralization system. it is estimated that <1 lb of material was discharged to the Ohio river

column168: Vehicle 1 a tractor pulling trailer 1 and trailer 2, was traveling northbound on US-93 near Elko County mile post 7.  Vehicle 1 drifted near the northbound fog line causing trailer 2 to drive off the roadway and go onto the dirt shoulder.  Driver then steered to the left, causing vehicle 1 and trailer 1 to travel in a northwest direction. Vehicle 1 then crossed the center line and went into the southbound lane. Trailer 2 then went off the roadway. Trailer 2 began to fishtail and then slid broadside. Trailer 2 then rolled over (531) onto its left side in the southbound lane. Upon impact or shortly after trailer two opened up spilling its contents, Vehicular Crash or Accident Damage (537). The driver then steered to the right bringing vehicle 1, trailer 1 and trailer 2 back into the northbound lane. Vehicle 1 and trailer 1 remained in the northbound lane, while trailer 2 came to rest on the northbound shoulder, in the dirt, on its left side, facing northwest.  The proper authorities were notified to report the spill (NRC, NVCA). A hazmat company was also notified for the initial spill response and latter the spill clean-up. The contaminated soil has been removed and the soil has been or is in the process of being replaced.  The tank failed because of the impact with the road surface, while sliding on the roadway the left side could have been abraded (301), ripped or torn (310) causing its content to leak (308).
column169: Continued training, a review of the accident in a safety meeting (what, when, where, how and why). Continued education on proper driving procedures and ways to prevent accidents e.g.(defensive driving techniques).

column168: Philadelphia Gas Works (PGW) has reviewed the available information relating to the diesel fuel release incident that occurred on September 28, 2011 in the vicinity of the Cottman Avenue exit from I-95 in Philadelphia, PA from a PGW owned Cargo Tank Motor Vehicle (CTMV).  As such, PGW has determined that there are several actions that can be taken in order to assist in avoiding another incident similar to the one that occurred on September 28, 2011, and they are listed as follows:    PGW has outsourced the majority of the fueling service operations to an outside vendor.  As such, the vendor will assume the responsibility of ensuring that all safety protocols associated with fuel transportation and fuel deliveries are implemented.  PGW will review the vendor’s safety plan and operating procedures to ensure that necessary steps are being taken to avoid future incidents.  By contracting with an outside vendor, PGW believes that the vendor’s expertise in the specialized area of fueling services will reduce the chances of a diesel fuel release.  PGW does intend to keep one or two (to be determined) CTMV’s available for backup and emergency situations only;    For the PGW CTMV/s that will be used as backup and emergencies, the hoses located on the CTMV’s will be encased in a material that reduces the chance of abrasion and hose failure such as that which occurred in September, which led to a diesel fuel release;    PGW will ensure that inspections of CTMV’s are conducted on a regular basis;  PGW operating procedures will be reviewed and updated as needed to ensure safety.
column169: Account #1    On Wednesday evening September 28, 2011 at approximately 9:15 pm I (Tina Roonan) received a call from Supply Chain’s driver1, Mr. Michael Hatala.  He advised me (Tina Roonan) that while on his way to Castor Station to fuel vehicles, he was traveling northbound on 95 approaching the off ramp for Cottman Ave. when he noticed smoke coming from the back of his truck, vehicle #5524.  He exited onto Cottman Avenue and traveled westbound crossing Torresdale Avenue and turned north onto Ditman Street, where he parked.      When he exited the vehicle he realized that diesel fuel was pouring out of the truck.  I (Tina Roonan) contacted Transportation and advised Mr. Ellis Steptoe and Mr. John McCoy of the situation.  John stated “he would send a mechanic up as soon as he could”.  Mr. Hatala then called me back and notified me that he was approached by a second alarmer (this is a volunteer that backs up the fire department) and notified Mr. Hatala that he was leaking diesel fuel, and it started back on the off ramp.  After being advised of the situation I (Tina Roonan) contacted Mr. John McCoy, advising him that the Fire Department was involved (and on the scene).  I (Tina Roonan) then left and went to the site of the incident.    When I (Tina Roonan) arrived on site various fireman were trying to stop the truck from leaking.  There were many fireman, police and equipment on site.  The fireman and equipment were from the 12th platoon out of the Hartel Street and Frankford Avenue fire station.  The Chief was Chief Fortuna.  They were able to stop the truck from leaking.  Mr. Robert Gonsiewski Supervisor, Industrial Waste Unit from the Philadelphia Water Department was on site to evaluate the situation surrounding the storm drain.  He approximated there to be approximately 30 gallons of diesel fuel that entered the storm drain.     Lieutenant George Cuthbert from the Hazardous Materials Administrative Unit of the Philadelphia Fire Department evaluated the site and labeled it a “Hazmat Site”.  He asked if PGW would hire their own Hazmat Contractor or if we (PGW representatives) would like him to do this for us.  Jo Ann Muniz via telephone requested that they bring in their contractor to perform the hazmat clean up.  He stated he would contact a company named “Clean Venture” to perform the clean up.  He also stated that a PGW supervisor must stay on site with the contractor until the clean up was completed.  Clean Venture arrived on site at approximately 12:30 am cleaned up the site along with the City of Philadelphia Streets Department, pumping approximately 75/80 gallons of a diesel/water mixture from the storm drain.  The clean up was completed at approximately 2:45 AM .    Account #2 (Steven Kernaghan)    The Clean Venture / Cycle Chem was contacted by the Philadelphia Fire Department Hazmat Division and Trevor Alexander the Lab Pack Chemist/Supervisor responded to the call. Clean up started around 12:30 am Thursday 9/29/2011 from the Cottman

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: An East Penn Driver was hauling a load of spent lead acid batteries from our West Babylon, NY warehouse to our secondary lead smelter in Lyons Station, PA.  While returning home on south I 95, mile marker 120/8, after crossing over the George Washington Bridge, another truck driver pulled up along side of him letting him know that he saw smoke coming out of his trailer and the he should pull over.  The driver pulled onto the shoulder of the road and called 911.  The driver and the other truck driver tried to extinguish the fire without success.  State police, Bergan County Haz Mat team, Turnpike Authorities and the LeOnia fire company arrived on the scene.    The driver did call back to Lyons Station to inform personnel of the incident.  The  Bergan County Haz Mat Team helped to contain the spill and also contacted Ken Marine Services for clean up after confirming with East Penn's Environmental Department.  The LeOnia Fire Department put out the fire.  NJ DEP also arrived on the scene.  According to the turnpike official and the Haz Mat team, there was run off into a near by storm drain.    The fire did burn a hole through the roof and buckled the sides of the trailer.  Ken's Marine transferred the junk batteries, after draining the acid from the batteries and over packing the drained spent batteries, onto another East Penn trailer.  The over packed batteries were shipped to EPM Lyon Station for proper disposal/recycle.  The acid and PPE from the clean up crew was disposed of as hazardous waste.    The NJ DEP did investigate the run off into the storm drain.  The outlet of the storm drain was tested before and after a rain with no change in pH.  The test was neutral.  According to the NJ DEP no more needed to be monitored.  All was clear.    The burnt trailer once emptied was towed to a near by scrap yard.  It was neutralized by Ken's Marine and disposed of as a neutralized waste solid to Cycle Chem, NJ.  The water used to clean the trailer was also captured and sent out as a Hazardous waste to Cycle Chern.    It is unknown how exactly the fire started.  It is assumed that 2, side terminal batteries touched causing an arch starting the fire.  The batteries are stacked on a wooden pallet with cardboard in between layers and stretch wrapped to the pallet.  The pallets are blocked and braced to prevent movement.
column169: A memo was sent out to ALL East Penn Warehouses, branches, subsidiaries and EPM drivers.  The memo re-instructed the proper packaging of side terminal batteries on the skid and the proper placement on the trailer.  The memo instructions were as follows:     - Make sure all batteries that have side terminals are stacked properly on a skid.  They must be stacked on the pallet so their terminals do not touch and other terminals of the same type or another battery type.   - If you know the pallet has quantities of side terminal batteries and your customer wrapped it, you need to open the pallet and check to make sure that the batteries were placed properly on the skid.   - If you have a full pallet of side terminal batteries, they are to be wrapped with cardboard around the outside of the pallet to protect the terminals even further.   - Make sure when you load pallets with side terminals on the trailer, be sure the pallets are positioned that no terminals on any side of the batteries are facing each other.

DSR was traveling back from XLF to XAY on WB I-80, near Route 62, near exit 234. It appears that our driver drifted off the road to the left hitting bridge.    The tractor was badly burnt as well as the dolly and lead trailer. About 60 gallons of diesel spilled from gas tank, as well as hazmat that was in one of the trailers.  No hazmat in other trailer.  Driver treated and released from the emergency room with bruises and 1st degree burns to his lower extremities. Fire extinguished.  Ohio EPA removed a possibly contaminated puddle near the scene.      From news reports: 'The Trumbull County HazMat team worked alongside others in the spot where a second trailer fell over the bridge. It landed in a field and no homes or businesses there. The first focus of the cleanup was the bridge area so it could re-open to traffic. That happened around 7 p.m. Wednesday. But as traffic started flowing again, HazMat workers and EPA officials were still busy. "Fortunately it went very smoothly for us. We were able to contain it and control it," Don Waldron, Trumbull County HazMat chief said. A green vacuum truck and storage container from Inland Environmental Emergency Response Service was sucking up the hazardous materials from the ground. It's then pumped into a bin and will eventually be hauled away. Waldron said there's no environmental concerns. Interstate Towing out of Macedonia was removing the semi-truck debris. The smell of leaked materials affected some of the workers.'  Agencies notified / On scene:  OEPA # 1109-78-2895, NRC - P.O. column42: NITRIC ACID OTHER THAN RED FUMING, WITH MORE THAN 70 PERCENT NITRIC ACID
column168: ON TUESDAY, SEPTEMBER 13, 2011, AT APPROXIMATELY 23:35, A TANK CAR WAS BEING LOADED WITH NITRIC ACID AND WAS OVER FILLED. AS SOON AS THE EMPLOYEE LOADING THE CAR NOTICED THAT THERE WAS A PROBLEM, HE CALLED FOR ASSISTANCE IMMEDIATELY AND LOADING WAS STOPPED. THE OVERFILLING CAUSED NITRIC ACID TO FLOW INTO THE VENT LINE ON THE RAIL CAR, FILLING THE LINE TO THE VENT SCRUBBER. WHEN THE SCRUBBER REACHED A HIGH LEVEL, NITRIC ACID WAS DISCHARED INTO A DITCH ON PLANT PROPERTY. THE DITCH WAS LINED, AND THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED. SODA ASH WAS USED TO NEUTRAILIZED THE SPILL AND THE MATERIAL WAS TRANSFERRED TO AN APPROVED AREA.  WEATHER AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT WAS NOT A FACTOR. THE WIND DIRECTION WAS FROM THE SOUTH AT 3 MPH AND THE AMBIENT TEMPERATURE WAS 79 DEGREES FARENHEIT. THERE WAS NO PRECIPATION AT THE TIME OF THE INCIDENT. THE SPILL WAS SECURED AT 23:45. THE SPILL DID NOT GO OFFSITE.
column169: 1.) A MEETING WAS HELD WITH ALL AFFECTED EMPLOYEES TO DISUCSS THE INCIDENT. THE FINDINGS OF THE INVESTIGATION AND CAUSAL FACTORS WERE DISCUSSED.  2.) ALL EMPLOYEES WERE RE-TRAINED ON THE CONTROL PANEL OPERATION.  3.) THE ROOT CAUSE OF THE INCIDENT WAS FOUND TO BE THAT THE PERSON LOADING THE RAIL CAR INADVERTENTLY 'ZEROED' THE SCALE WHILE THE PRODUCT WAS BEING LOADED, THEREFORE OVERLOADING THE CAR. WARNING LABELS WERE ADDED TO THE SCALE CONTROL PANEL DESCRIBING THE POTENTIAL OF SUCH AS INCIDENT.  4.)A LIQUID SENSOR WILL BE INSTALLED IN THE VENT LINE WITH AN ALARM RINGING IN TO THE LOADING AREA AND TO THE CONTROL BOARD IF A LIQUID LEVEL IS DETECTED.

column168: SEE: ATTACHED ROOT CAUSE ANALYSIS & LETTER ADDRESSED TO INFORMATION SYSTEMS MANAGER.  NOTE: DUE TO FACT THAT SPILL WAS LESS THAN < GAL IT DID NOT MEET REQUIREMENTS OF 171.15 FOR REPORTING, HOWEVER WE FELT THAT SINCE A SMALL QUANTITY DID REACH A NAVIGABLE WATERWAY IT WAS REPORTED.  NOTE: REPORT DELAYED DUE TO CHANGE OF ADDRESS.  DURING TRANSFER OF PRODUCT FROM RAIL CAR TO TANK #19, A, CAM LOC FITTING FAILED. APPROXIMATELY 100 BBLS WAS SPILLED AND CONTAINED INSIDE THE DIKE. A SMALL AMOUNT OF CRUDE OIL MAXIMUM 5 GALLONS LEAKED AROUND THE CONTAINMENT PIPE POSSIBLY DUE TO SOIL SHRINKAGE WITH EXTREME DROUGHT. MOST OF OIL WAS SOAKED UP WITH ABSORBANT PADS. HAZMAT TEAMS WERE NOTIFIED TO RESPOND AND FINISH CLEANUP PROCEDURES. ABSORBANT PADS DISPENSED AND 99% OF OIL WAS SOAKED UP. CONTACTED LOCAL HAZMAT COMPANY ES&H TO CLEAN UP REMAINING OIL.
column169: SEE LETTER.  REMEDIATION PLAN:  1. AREA AROUND THE CONCRETE SUMP WILL BE PRESSURE WASHED WITH HOT WATER.  2. OIL STAINED VEGETATION WAS REMOVED AND RAKED UP.  3. OIL STAINED SOIL HAS BEEN REMOVED TO A DEPTH OF 1/4" TO 1/2" WITH FLAT HEAD SHOVELS AND PROPERLY DISPOSED OF.  4. AREA WILL BE ACCESSED FOR FURTHER TREATMENT IF NECESSARY BY FOLLOW UP INSPECTIONS WITH DEQ.    ACCIDENT PREVENTION MEASURES:  1. THE SPILL WAS CAUSED BY DEFECTIVE CASTING RESULTING IN A CAM LOC FAILURE.  2. ALL CAMLOC FITTINGS WILL BE REPLACED WITH NEW FITTINGS.  3. WHERE APPLICABLE CAMLOC CONNECTIONS AND HOSES WILL BE REPLACED WITH HARD PIPE CONNECTIONS.  4. THE STORM DRAIN WAS REMOVED ON N SIDE OF CONTAINMENT AND FILLED WITH FLOW ABLE FILL CONCRETE, ELIMINATING ANY FUTURE BREACHES IN CONTAINMENT AREA OR ROUTES OF DISCHARGE TO THE WATER.  5. DUE TO THE AGE OF EXISTING CONTAINMENT DISCHARGE VALVES WILL BE CUT, PLUGGED OR REMOVED ELIMINATING THE POSSIBLE ROUTE OF PRODUCT REACHING THE RIVER.  6. WE WILL INVESTIGATE DEVICES TO DETECT SPILLS IN VALVE MANIFOLD AREAS AND PUMP CONTAINMENT TO IMMEDIATELY ALERT OPERATORS IN THE EVENT OF A FUTURE SPILL.  7. EXISTING PROCEDURES WILL BE EVALUATED FOR CONTINUOUS IMPROVEMENT.

While delivering a partial load of molten sulphur, Savage Driver came up upon a 3rd-party vehicle almost stationary in the road.  As the Savage Driver proceeded to pass the 3rd-party vehicle in left lane, the 3rd-party turned directly into the Savage tractor/trailer.  Savage Driver struck 3rd-party vehicle and as a result of the impact tried to recover control of tractor/trailer.  The tractor/trailer rolled over blocking the road.  Savage employee was transported to the hospital via ambulance.  Approximatley less than 10 gallons of sulphur was released as a result of the rollover accident.  Emergency responders used a water fog spray to cool and solidify the molten sulfur to stop the release from the leaking dome lid.

column168: THE TRANSPORT DRIVER OVER FILLED AN UNDERGROUND GASOLINE STORAGE TANK AT A CONVENIENCE STORE. THE DRIVER WAS IN THE CAB OF THE TRUCK WHILE OFF LOADING TO THE TANK. ONCE THE TANK REACHED THE LIMIT OF THE OVERFILL VALVE THE GASKET ON THE OFF LOADING SPOUT ALLOWED GASOLINE TO LEAK BY. THE GASOLINE THEN RAN DOWN A SIDE STREET, ABOUT 300 YARDS, INTO THE YARD OF A RESIDENCE. WE IMMEDIATELY CALLED AN EMERGENCY HAZ-MAT SPILL RESPONSE TEAM TO RESPOND TO THE SITE. ALL OF THE PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED TO A SMALL AREA OF THE YARD. THE ODORS FROM THE GASOLINE MADE IT UNCOMFORTABLE FOR SOME RESIDENTS AND WE EVACUATED THEM TO MOTELS FOR THE REMAINDER OF THE NIGHT. THEY WERE ABLE TO RETURN TO THEIR HOMES THE FOLLOWING MORNING.  UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF A LICENSED GEOLOGIST THE HAZ-MAT RESPONSE COMPANY EXCAVATED THE IMPACTED SOIL FROM THE YARD OF THE RESIDENCE. SOIL SAMPLES WERE TAKEN AND RESULTS REPORTED TO THE NORTH CAROLINA DEPARTMENT OF NATURAL RESOURCES. WE HAVE RECEIVED A NO FURTHER ACTION NECESSARY LETTER FROM NC DENR.
column169: THE DRIVER WAS IN VIOLATION OF COMPANY POLICY BY NOT STANDING BY THE VALVES OF THE TANKER THAT CONTROLS THE PRODUCT FLOW DURING OFF LOADING. THE DRIVER WAS TERMINATED. ALL OTHER DRIVERS WERE RETRAINED ON OFF LOADING PRODCEDURES, INSPECTION AND REQUIRED ROUTINE MAINTENANCE OF THE FIXTURES AND HOSES USED TO OFF LOAD PRODUCT.

column168: TRANSPORT DRIVER DANNY VAUGHT WAS TRAVELING EASTBOUND ON HWY 70. DANNY HAD A LOT OF CARS BEHIND HIM SO HE USED THE TURN OUT AT PULGA FLATS TO LET CARS PASS HIM. AT THAT TIME A CALTRANS PLOW PULLED OUT THEIR GATE INTO THE TURN OUT LANE, HIS PLOW HIT THE FRONT TIRE OF THE PULL TRAILER THEN THE PLOW BLADE HIT THE PIPING UNDER THE TRAILER TEARING IT OPEN AND PULLED THE CABLE TO THE INTERNAL VALVE OPEN ALLOWING 1 COMPARTMENT CONTAINING 1800 GALLONS OF GASOLINE TO SPILL OUT ON THE SHOULDER OF THE HIGHWAY. DANNY TRIED THE EMERGENCY SHUT OFF BUT THE CABLE WAS WRAPPED UP IN THE DAMAGED PIPING AND HE COULD NOT RELEASE IT. IT TOOK ABOUT 5 MINS TO EMPTY THE COMPARTMENT THROUGH THE HOLE IN THE PIPE. THE SKIN OR SHELL WAS NOT DAMAGED, JUST THE DISCHARGE PIPE. DANNY GOT HIS SPILL KIT OUT AND DIRECTED THE SPILL OFF THE ROADWAY.
column169: I HAVE INSTRUCTED ALL DRIVERS NOT TO USE THAT TURN OUT AS IT IS IN FRONT OF A DRIVEWAY TO THE CALTRANS FACILITY. I WOULD RECOMMEND THAT CALTRANS ELIMINATE THE TURNOUT AT THAT LOCATION AND INSTRUCT THE CALTRANS EMPLOYEES TO BE CAREFUL WHEN PULLING OUT THERE GATE ONTO A ROADWAY ESPECIALLY WHEN THEY ARE DRIVING A PLOW TRUCK WHERE THE PLOW PROTRUDES SEVERAL FEET OUT IN FRONT OF THE VEHICLE.

column168: SEPTEMBER 11, 2011, HIALEAH TRANSPORT FUEL TANKER OVERTURNED ONTO THE NORTHBOUND LANES OF U.S. HWY 27 AT MILE MARKER 79.1. A FIRE STARTED, AFTER WHICH THE TANKER COMPARTMENTS EXPLODED. FUEL BOTH BURNED OFF AND LEAKED ONTO THE ADJACENT PAVEMENT AND GROUND. THE AMOUNTS BURNED OFF VERSUS LEAKED INTO THE GROUND ARE NOT KNOWN. THE FLORIDA HIGHWAY PATROL AND (    ) FIRE DEPARTMENT RESPONDED TO THE ACCIDENT. A DECISION WAS MADE TO LET THE FIRE CONTINUE BURNING. ONCE THE FIRE BURNED OUT, AN ENVIRONMENTAL INVESTIGATION WAS STARTED TO DETERMINE THE EXTENT OF THE DAMAGE. PETROLEUM IMPACTS TO THE SOIL AND GROUNDWATER WERE CONFIRMED. EXCAVATION OF THE SOIL AND PUMPING OF GROUNDWATER WAS PERFORMED TO MITIGATE THE DAMGES. AN ALTERNATIVE PROCEDURE WAS APPROVED BY THE FLORIDA DEPARTMENT OF ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION TO AID IN THE REMEDIATION OF THE SOIL AND GROUNDWATER.  ADDITIONAL ASSESSMENT WILL NEED TO BE PERFORMED.
column169: AN ADDENDUM TO THIS REPORT WILL DESCRIBE THE ACTION TO BE TAKEN TO PREVENT RECURRENCE.

column168: SUMMARY OF RESPONSE TO GASOLINE SPILL NEAR BIG BEAR, CALIFORNIA    (Based upon a site visit by Brown and Caldwell on September 23, 2011, and follow up communication/monitoring via telephone and email with various state, federal, and local agencies, as well as contractors.)    RELEASE INFORMATION    The incident began at approximately 10:30 PM on Monday, September 19, 2011with a tanker truck operated by Silvana Pelleche Trucking overturning on SR-38 near milepost 23.7.  The tanker was traveling eastbound (uphill)  with a load of approximately 8,200 to 8,400 gallons of gasoline for delivery to a gas station  in Big Bear, California.  The tanker turned over on its right side and slid into a low earthen embankment on the south side of SR-38. The driver was apparently  unhurt.  All compartments of the approximately 9,000-gallon capacity tanker were punctured and the fuel leaked onto the bare ground between the roadway and the embankment. Most of the fuel from the tanker spilled onto the ground and ran downhill (southwest) along the south side of SR-38 until it reached an informal drainage  basin that trended back to the east toward a flowing waterway, Forsee Creek, a tributary of the Santa Ana River. The gasoline ponded In the drainage basin behind a berm which prevented it from entering the creek.  The tanker's  inverted diesel fuel tanks also spilled up to roughly 100 gallons of fuel onto the roadway through the fill ports.  The diesel fuel and crankcase oil ran across the road to the northwest where it was absorbed by another earthen  embankment.  The CA Highway Patrol, Caltrans, and local fire departments responded to the incident. The U.S. Forest Service also had representatives at the scene.  The CHP and Caltrans contacted emergency response contractor Double Barrel Environmental Services (DBES) for assistance with the emergency response actions.  Dean Matsuoka was the first DBES employee on the scene.  According to Mr. Matsuoka, two vacuum tanker trucks  were ordered to the scene, which were able to recover approximately 1,000 gallons of fuel from the tanker and 1,200 gallons of fuel from the ponded area in the acijacent drainage basin.    Based on DBES' account  of the incident, 6,000 gallons of fuel were released into environment, primarily by soaking into the ground.  The fuel traveled overland approximately 200 to 250 feet to the southwest and then east into the drainage basin.  The incident  occurred in a rather steep-sided ravine that was partially filled for the roadway.  The site was underlain  by unconsolidated gravelly sand beneath the roadway and turnout.   Native materials beneath the road bed consisted of a veneer of sand and gravel alluvial soil over fractured granitic rock.  The area beyond the road and turnout was lightly to densely vegetated with native shrubs, grasses, and mature trees.  The truck crash apparently  occurred  on the Caltrans right-of-way.
